# ESPHome Firmware Architecture Implementation Plan - Phase 4

This implementation plan covers **Phase 4: HiveMQ Integration & Rule Engine**. The goals of this phase are to implement the dynamic tokenized rule engine with hysteresis (anti-oscillation) filters, set up the periodic asynchronous `SensorTask` on Core 1, establish the secure HiveMQ MQTT over TLS connection on Core 0, and implement the hybrid fallback connection pipeline.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> - **MQTT Library choice**: We propose using standard `PubSubClient` combined with ESP32's `WiFiClientSecure` to handle MQTT over TLS (Port 8883) securely. This library compiles easily and is highly reliable for dual-core setups.
> - **HiveMQ Root CA**: HiveMQ Cloud uses Let's Encrypt certificates. We will hardcode the standard ISRG Root X1 CA certificate in a header file `HiveMQ_CA.h` (or load it from `/system.json`) to allow secure TLS handshakes.
> - **Sensor Mocking**: Unless you have a physical DHT/BMP sensor connected to specific pins, we will generate mock temperature/humidity values inside `SensorTask` that drift dynamically (to simulate changes for rule evaluation).
> - **Relay Pins**: We will register a dummy load (e.g., GPIO 13, named `"fan_relay"`) via `HardwareManager` to demonstrate rule-driven actuator toggling.

